  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Emergency Response to the COVID-19 Epidemic in Western Bahr el Ghazal</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">On April 5th 2020, South Sudan confirmed its first COVID-19 case within its borders. The announcement did not come as a surprise for the humanitarian community as the country was one of the last ones in Africa to not report any cases despite the fact that the number of cases at its borders has been consistently increasing over the last few weeks. Although the announcement of an additional case in South Sudan on April 7th cannot be interpreted as a sign of large spread of the disease, it surely isn&#x2019;t a positive indicator for the South Sudanese population. Indeed, if the two confirmed cases are both employees of the same international organisation in Juba, official sources declared they did not have contact between each other thus indicating there are other cases undetected. More importantly, uncertainty remains high on the actual caseload of contaminated individuals as only very few number of tests, around thirty, have been conducted since the beginning of the crisis, underlying the lack of capacity of the health sector to face such outbreak.

Should COVID-19 spread across the country, as it will unfortunately most likely be the case, there is no doubt that the health system will not be able to respond effectively as the health facilities coverage is particularly weak due to inadequate human resources, funding and essential commodities. As detailed in the START FUND alert raised on April 6th, only approximately 1,000 health facilities providing healthcare services are functional while only two ventilators are available in the whole country (although essential equipment in case of respiratory complications due to COVID-19). As South Sudan is already facing a worrying humanitarian situation with almost half of all counties having a convergence of high needs related to food insecurity, protection, and water, sanitation and hygiene (WASH), thorough preparedness is an essential mean to limit the epidemic spread and impact.</narrative>
  </description>
